<h2 id="how-does-wtc-improve-its-model-over-time">How does WTC improve its model over time?</h2>

<p>A false negative is not a big deal for WTC, and, in the spirit of keeping things lightweight, they don‚Äôt feel very much pressure for continuous monitoring and improvement.</p>

<figure class="figure">

    

    

    

    
        <div class="post-img">
        <!-- Add the 'boxed' class if 'box' attribute is 'yes' -->
        <img src="../images/2022/WTC-flow.webp" alt="What's that charge improvement flow" class=" " style="border-radius: 20px; max-width: 100%" srcset="../images/2022/WTC-flow.webp 2x%" loading="lazy" />
    </div>
    <figcaption></figcaption>
        

</figure>

<p>They have set a modest confidence threshold of 80%, meaning that Nyckel will only flag a comment for human moderation when the ML model is less than 80% confident in its own classification of the comment. Whether or not a human reviewer disagrees with the ML classification, the result is fed back to the model, making it more accurate. Furthermore, if WTC notices that the model is in fact correctly classifying comments but flagging too many of them for review, they can adjust down the confidence threshold, allowing a greater proportion of the moderation to be automated.</p>

<div class="customer-quote-block" style="padding-left:5%;padding-right:15%">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-sm-8">
            <div class="customer-quote p-10">"It‚Äôs kind of amazing that What‚Äôs That Charge can get better without even touching the code."</div>
